  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "NJnqmL6IDT9SU2jwLGpmyslRiwc=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:46.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Claim\nPull is manifest-driven: poll user feed \u2192 read user manifest \u2192 per-document manifests \u2192 batch references \u2192 /bytes downloads \u2192 decrypt \u2192 inbox.\n\n## Step-by-step\n1. SwarmChannel polls the user's feed at the configured interval (`pollIntervalMs`).\n2. Reads the user manifest \u2192 discovers drives and documents.\n3. For each document, reads its manifest \u2192 discovers operation batches.\n4. Downloads each batch from `/bytes`, decrypts with AES-256-GCM, deserializes.\n5. Converts to `SyncOperation` objects and adds to `SwarmChannel.inbox`.\n6. SyncManager applies them to the local reactor via `reactor.load()`.\n7. Cursor advances in `sync_cursors`; subsequent polls only fetch new operations.\n\n## Implications\n- First load on a new device walks the full manifest tree but only applies each batch once.\n- Steady-state pulls are cheap \u2014 only new manifest entries trigger downloads.\n- The manifest tree is the discovery index; without it, the pull cannot proceed.\n\n## Source\nSwarm Channel Architecture, \"Pull Cycle (Swarm \u2192 local)\".",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:46.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:46.000Z"
    }
  },
